le of Willis","Union of the two posterior communicating arteries"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eunion of the two vertebral arteries\u003C/strong\u003E forms the basilar artery at the pontomedullary junction. The basilar artery then ascends along the ventral surface of the pons before terminating by dividing into the two posterior cerebral arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranch of the internal carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The internal carotid arteries contribute to anterior circulation, not the basilar artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuation of the anterior spinal artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The anterior spinal artery descends along the spinal cord and is not involved in basilar artery formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranch of the circle of Willis\u003C/strong\u003E - The basilar artery contributes to the circle of Willis but is not a branch of it\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnion of the two posterior communicating arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The posterior communicating arteries connect the internal carotid arteries to the posterior cerebral arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe basilar artery is a crucial vessel that supplies blood to the brainstem, cerebellum, and portions of the temporal and occipital lobes through various branches including the anterior inferior cerebellar, superior cerebellar, and pontine arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The basilar artery is formed by the union of the two vertebral arteries at the pontomedullary junction.","The basilar artery supplies blood to the pons, midbrain, cerebellum and parts of the temporal and occipital lobes.","The basilar artery terminates by dividing into the two posterior cerebral arteries."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cCircle of Willis\u201d by Rhcastilhos is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0) \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Circle_of_Willis_en.svg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55893"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17394"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21312"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21312"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/djDvSCBJltLWjwZ3HmrxBxXmWbeUyX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/djDvSCBJltLWjwZ3HmrxBxXmWbeUyX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":1008}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55893"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T09:25:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T09:26:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10084"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70429"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":